{{DEFAULTSORT:なかたけおんせん}} [[Category:北海道の温泉]] [[Category:野湯]] [[Category:大雪山]] [[Category:東川町]] [[Category:Pages to be translated]] [[Category:Pages to be overwritten]] [[ja:中岳温泉]] {{DEFAULTSORT:Nakadake Hot Spring}}

{{Japanese Hot Spring Resort |Name = Nakadake Onsen |image = Nakadake hotspring daisetuzan01.jpg |Comment = Open‐air bath at Nakadake Onsen; the rock beside the tub is used as a clothes resting spot. |Location = {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道}} {{ill|Kamikawa-gun|ja|上川郡}} {{ill|Tōkawa Town|ja|東川町}} |Access = Approximately 1 hour 10 minutes by bus from {{ill|Asahikawa City|ja|旭川市}}; then take a {{ill|ropeway|ja|ロープウェイ}} to disembark at Sugami-no-ike, followed by about 2 hours on foot. |Water Type = |Temperature = |Discharge = |pH = |Liquid Classification = |Osmotic Pressure Classification = |Number of Accommodations = |Total Capacity = |Annual Bath Visitors = |Statistical Year = |External links = |Special Notes = }}
[[Image:Daisetsu-zan in summer.jpg|thumb|right|Snowy, swan-like ice formations visible along the access road (July 2006)]] [[Image:Hotsprings and maintenance-tool Nakadake hotspring daisetuzan02.jpg|thumb|right|The hot spring tub and a maintenance shovel]]
'''Nakadake Onsen''' (中岳温泉) is an undeveloped {{ill|wild hot spring|ja|野湯}} that bubbles up on the mid-slope of {{ill|Nakadake|ja|中岳}} in the {{ill|Daisetsuzan|ja|大雪山}} – {{ill|Asahidake|ja|旭岳}} mountain range, located in {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道}}, {{ill|Kamikawa-gun|ja|上川郡}}, {{ill|Tōkawa Town|ja|東川町}}.
== Water Quality == The water has a distinct {{ill|sulfur odor|ja|硫黄臭}}. The source water is extremely hot—so hot that it must be tempered before use. To adjust the temperature, water is drawn from a nearby stream running from a {{ill|snow field|ja|雪渓}} by constructing a hot spring channel ({{ill|Yudō|ja|湯道}}) using tools such as a {{ill|shovel|ja|シャベル}}.
== Onsen Area == The rock adjacent to the bathing tub serves as a makeshift changing area. Aside from the dug-out tub and hiking trails, no other man-made structures are present in this wild hot spring. The surrounding area is overgrown with {{ill|High Mats|ja|ハイマツ}} and adorned with blooming {{ill|Tsugazakura|ja|ツガザクラ}}, attracting outdoor enthusiasts to this authentic, secret hot spring. However, prolonged bathing may be inadvisable during certain seasons. In some periods, a large number of {{ill|horseflies|ja|虻}} may emerge, and gathering in the open without cover is risky. In addition, since the area is a habitat for {{ill|brown bears|ja|ヒグマ}}, it is essential to carry a bell or take other bear deterrence measures.
== Access == From {{ill|Asahikawa City|ja|旭川市街}}, take a bus to {{ill|Asahidake Onsen|ja|旭岳温泉}} (approximately 1 hour 10 minutes). Then, board a ropeway and disembark at Sugami-no-ike, followed by about 2 hours of hiking. This route passes through a plateau known as Susuge-daira, offering views of the majestic {{ill|Asahidake|ja|旭岳}} to the right, and traverses a flower field where {{ill|Chinguruma|ja|チングルマ}} bloom. Alternatively, one may descend westward from the Nakadake branch along the route from {{ill|Mamiya-dake|ja|間宮岳}} to Nakadake.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Hokkaido no Yama|author=Kenji Itō|publisher=Yama to Keikoku-sha|date=2017}}</ref>
== References == {{脚注のヘルプ}} {{Reflist}}
== Further Reading == * Kenji Itō, ''Hokkaido no Yama'' (Yama to Keikoku-sha, 2017)
